üîπ FX OPTION (Business Product)
What it is
Gives right (not obligation) to exchange currency at fixed rate
Customer decides whether to use it

Key Points
Premium paid upfront
Maximum loss = premium
Settlement only if exercised
Used for hedging FX risk

Lifecycle
Booked ‚Üí Active ‚Üí Waiting ‚Üí Exercised / Expired ‚Üí Closed

Money Flow
Booking ‚Üí Premium posted
Exercise ‚Üí Currency exchange
Expiry (no exercise) ‚Üí No settlement
One-Line Rule

FX Option = Choice + Premium + Limited Risk

üîπ ETD (Exchange-Traded Derivative)
What it is
Standardized contract traded on exchange
Mandatory settlement

Key Points
No premium
Margin required
Daily MTM (Mark-to-Market)
Loss can be unlimited

Lifecycle
Trade ‚Üí Daily MTM ‚Üí Margin Calls ‚Üí Settlement ‚Üí Close

Money Flow
Daily profit/loss settled
Margin adjusted every day
Final settlement is compulsory

One-Line Rule
ETD = Obligation + Daily P&L + Mandatory Settlement

üîπ FXPM (FX Product Management)
What it is
NOT a product
Core processing engine for FX products

Handles
Validation
Lifecycle management
Accounting
Settlement
Reporting & events

Used For
FX Option
ETD
FX Forward
FX Cash

Key Points
Same engine, different product rules
Independent of input (OFS / TIS / UI)
Central focus for automation

One-Line Rule
FXPM = Engine that processes FX trades

| Aspect     | FX Option | ETD       | FXPM        |
| ---------- | --------- | --------- | ----------- |
| Type       | Product   | Product   | Engine      |
| Choice     | Yes       | No        | N/A         |
| Premium    | Yes       | No        | N/A         |
| Margin     | No        | Yes       | Manages     |
| Daily MTM  | No        | Yes       | Executes    |
| Settlement | Optional  | Mandatory | Enforces    |
| Risk       | Limited   | High      | Operational |



******************                         ETD (Exchange-Traded Derivatives)                *************************

ETD are derivative contracts (their value comes from an underlying like stocks, indices, FX, commodities) that are traded on a regulated exchange with standardized terms.
Common ETD types

Futures ‚Äì obligation to buy/sell at a future date & price
Options ‚Äì right (not obligation) to buy/sell
Index derivatives ‚Äì Nifty, S&P 500, FTSE, etc.
Commodity derivatives ‚Äì Gold, Oil, Agri products

You expect ABC stock to rise next month.
Today price: ‚Çπ1,000
You buy ABC Futures @ ‚Çπ1,020 (1-month expiry)
After 1 month:
Price = ‚Çπ1,080 ‚Üí Profit = ‚Çπ60
Price = ‚Çπ980 ‚Üí Loss = ‚Çπ40
You didn‚Äôt buy the stock directly; you traded its future price.

ETD trade lifecycle (high level)
Trade placed on exchange
Margin blocked
Trade matched
Clearing house novates (becomes buyer to seller & vice-versa)
Daily MTM (Mark-to-Market)
Expiry / square-off / physical or cash settlement


ETD in banking & trading systems (like T24)
Used for hedging (FX, interest rate, equity risk)
Automated margin, MTM, expiry, settlement
Strong controls & validations ‚Üí good for STP

ETD = standardized derivative contracts traded on exchanges, cleared by a clearing house, offering transparency, liquidity, and reduced counterparty risk.


üü¢ Inbound (‚û°Ô∏è coming IN to T24)
Inbound = data / message / request that comes INTO Temenos T24 from outside systems

Think like this üëá  -->  Inbound = someone tells T24 to do something

ETD examples (Inbound)
Trade sent from Trading System / Exchange
File or API message asking T24 to book a trade
Message to update trade details


üîµ Outbound (‚¨ÖÔ∏è going OUT from T24)

Outbound = data / message / notification that goes FROM T24 to other systems

Think like this üëá --> Outbound = T24 tells others what happened

ETD examples (Outbound)
Margin posting sent to Accounting / GL
MTM result sent to Risk system
Settlement confirmation sent to Exchange / Back office


Exchange / Trading App
        |
        | (Inbound: Trade request)
        v
     T24 ETD Module
        |
        | (Outbound: Margin / MTM / Settlement)
        v
 Accounting / GL / Risk / Reports



    **************    EDT  **************
	Asset Type √ó Instrument Type √ó Settlement √ó Premium Style √ó Actor √ó Event

	DX Trade (DX.TRADE) -->
	A derivative contract booked in T24 ETD module
	
	
	Used for:
           Options
           Futures
           Options on Futures (OFU)
		   
		   
		   SAT (Sub Asset Type) --> SAT tells T24 WHAT instrument family this is.
		   
| SAT | Meaning                  |
| --- | ------------------------ |
| 401 | Equity Option (Physical) |
| 407 | Equity Option (Cash)     |
| 416 | Equity Index Option      |
| 446 | Equity Index OFU         |
| 447 | Corporate Bond Index OFU |
| 449 | Precious Metal OFU       |
| 413 | Interest Rate OFU        |
| 445 | FX OFU                   |
                                    Note --> SAT decides ‚Üí settlement logic + accounting formula + lifecycle path
									
									
									
| Type       | Meaning                             |
| ---------- | ----------------------------------- |
| **Option** | Right, not obligation               |
| **Future** | Obligation                          |
| **OFU**    | Option whose underlying is a Future |


   OFU = Option on Futures
   Used heavily in:
   Equity Index
   IR
   FX
   Commodity
   
   Premium Style --> Premium style = WHEN money is charged
   
   Option Style (Pay first)):
   Premium exchanged at inception
   Real cash movement immediately

   Real-life example
   You book a movie ticket:
                           You pay first
                           Then you watch movie
In T24 terms : Premium is paid at trade booking (inception) , Happens before expiry / exercise / assignment , Money moves immediately

If Premium Style = OPTION
‚úî Check premium at DX.TRADE creation
‚úî Do NOT expect premium later

   Future Style:
   NO premium at inception
   Settlement happens at: 
Assignment (Seller is forced) : SELL to Open option
Exercise (Buyer chooses): BUY to Open option
Expiry (No one acts): Both BUY and SELL sides
Real-life example : Option expires , No one exercised or assigned.
Maturity (Futures only): FUTURES, not options   , Future contract reaches end date.


| Premium Style | Settlement timing                        |
| ------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Option Style  | Premium at booking + settlement at event |
| Future Style  | Settlement only at event                 |

Buy ‚Üí Exercise
Sell ‚Üí Assignment
Do nothing ‚Üí Expiry
Future ‚Üí Maturity



In T24 terms
No premium at inception
Money moves during lifecycle event
Settlement happens at: Exercise , Assignment , Expiry ,Maturity

Real-life example
You go to restaurant:
Eat first
Pay after eating

üëâ This is FUTURE premium style

   Future Style = ‚ÄúAccounting is deferred‚Äù

If Premium Style = FUTURE
‚úî No premium at booking
‚úî Expect payout during event
   
   Buy to Open / Sell to Open  -->
   üß† Accounting rule
   Sell to Open ‚Üí payout risk
   Buy to Open ‚Üí payout benefit
   
| Action       | Meaning                               |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------- |
| Buy to Open  | You buy the option                    |
| Sell to Open | You sell the option (take obligation) |


      Own Book vs Client -->
	  
| Type     | Meaning                          |
| -------- | -------------------------------- |
| Client   | Bank acts as intermediary        |
| Own Book | Bank takes risk on its own books |


  Own Book indicators
  Sector = 9002
  PL accounts involved (PL52001, PL53421)
     
   
   Broker / Eurex / A1   -->
| Term   | Meaning                     |
| ------ | --------------------------- |
| Broker | OTC / external counterparty |
| Eurex  | Exchange traded             |
| A1     | Clearing broker             |

   üß† Eurex
Requires: Suppress Underlying = YES
          Sec Trade creation
		  Clearing settlement
		  
		  
		  1. Assignment -->
		  Used when:
        Option holder exercises
        Seller must deliver
		
		Results:
          Trade ‚Üí CLOSED
          PRI LOTS = 0
          SEC LOTS = 0
		  DX CLOSEOUT ID generated
		  
		  2. Exercise
          Used when:Option buyer chooses to exercise
		  Results:
          Sec trade created (IHLD)
		  Settlement posted
		  Resultant trade (101) may be created
		  
		 3. Expiry
         Used when: Option expires worthless or ITM/OTM logic applies
		 Results:
         No new risk
         Positions closed
         Accounting depends on ITM/OTM
		 
		 4. Maturity (Futures)
            Used only for:
                     Futures
                     OFU underlying settlement
					 
					 
		5. Rectification (Event 300)
             When: Wrong trade booked ,Reversal needed		

                Original Trade
                   ‚Üì Reverse
                New Trade (Event 300)
				
		Used heavily in:
                Eurex
                OFU
                FutureStyle
				
		6. Resultant Trade (Event 101)
            Purpose: Accounting , Reporting ,Regulatory trace
            Created after: Assignment ,Exercise ,Expiry (sometimes)

          Cash Settlement : Notional = Lots √ó Contract Size
          Physical Settlement : Notional = Lots √ó Contract Size √ó Strike Price

        Typical Accounting Entries
        Sell to Open (Own Book)
               Debit/Credit:
                            PL53421
                            Broker Nostro
               Buy to Open :
			   Opposite flow	


          üîπ DX Closeout ID
                    Generated when:
                                Trade lifecycle ends
      Used to:
         Link PRI & SEC settlements
         Tie accounting entries

 | Side | Meaning                       |
| ---- | ----------------------------- |
| PRI  | Primary (client / own book)   |
| SEC  | Secondary (broker / exchange) |

Note --> Both must go to zero for closure.


Cash settlement -->  Lots √ó Contract Size
Physical settlement --> Lots √ó Contract Size √ó Strike Price

												  
